  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">STAR Call 1-Strengthening Community-led initiatives for Peaceful and credible Elections (SCOPE)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">At the end of 12 months period, the SCOPE project should have measured the following results; &#x2022; 472 community thumb printing clinic facilitators (118 each of elderly females, young females, elderly males and young males) identified and trained in implementing districts for targeted voter education &#x2022; In areas where physically challenged people are identified, they shall be mobilized to have a separate clinic with one of them as a facilitator. &#x2022; 472 thumb printing clinic facilitators in implementing districts have mobilised and held peer to peer thumb printing clinics reaching out 18,880 voters (4,720 young
males and young female, 14,160 each of elderly males and elderly females) &#x2022; 118 community election vigilante groups formed ((with 40% women representation) and trained from existing community groups as whistle blowers for real time emerging violence issues to the District Security Emergency Committees (DISEC). &#x2022; 118 community election vigilante groups have reached out to 41</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The democratic process of Ghana has been improving since 1992. The country adopted a multi-party democracy in 1992 with a promulgation of a constitution and has since organized six presidential and parliamentary elections. The New Patriotic Party (NPP) has ruled for 8 years while the National Democratic Congress ruled for 16 years. Elections in Ghana have always been characterized by tensions with prayer camps springing up from all corners of the country just to ensure violence free and peaceful election. Citizens in most parts of the country are not well targeted for voter education, electoral education
and their general civic rights. It is true that there has been increased citizens&#x2019; participation in elections but attention has been given more to electoral education over voter education resulting in increased numbers of rejected ballots from the increasing voter turn-out. As high as 1,552 rejected ballots in Central Gonja with the 43.3% voter turn-out in the 2015 District Level Election as per the records of the Electoral Commission. Political parties are mandated to carry out voter education. Such voter education only reaches a few fortunate ones (party activists).</narrative>
  </description>
